      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Should You Sell or Hold Your Brisbane Investment Property?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        It is one of the hardest decisions in property investment because it involves tax, cash flow, opportunity cost, and personal circumstances simultaneously. Here is a framework that cuts through the noise.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most investment decisions have a relatively clear objective: maximise return, manage risk, or achieve a specific financial goal. The sell-or-hold decision is harder because it sits at the intersection of all three, and because it involves tax consequences that are not immediately obvious, emotional attachment to an asset you may have owned for years, and uncertainty about what you would do with the capital if you did sell. There is no formula that spits out the right answer. But there is a structured way to think through it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The factors that point toward selling</h2>
      <p>Several conditions, individually or in combination, suggest that selling is likely the better financial decision.</p>

      <p>The property has significantly appreciated and the CGT liability is manageable. If you bought an inner east Brisbane investment property a decade ago and it has doubled in value, you are sitting on a substantial unrealised gain. At some point, locking in that gain and redeploying the capital into a higher-performing asset, or simply reducing debt elsewhere, produces a better net financial outcome than continuing to hold. The question is whether the tax cost of realising the gain is justified by what you can do with the proceeds.</p>

      <p>The rental yield is low relative to your cost of capital. If the gross rental yield on your investment is 3.5% and your mortgage rate is 6%, you are running a negative cash flow position. That can be acceptable when capital growth is strong and you have the income to support it. But if capital growth has moderated, holding a negatively geared asset that is also not growing meaningfully is a poor combination. The cost of holding is real and compounding.</p>

      <p>The negative gearing offset no longer serves your tax position. Negative gearing is only useful if you have assessable income to offset. If your income has reduced, if you have retired, or if your income structure has changed, the tax benefit of negative gearing shrinks significantly. An asset you were holding partly for the tax benefit may no longer justify the carry cost without that benefit.</p>

      <p>The property requires significant capital expenditure. A major roof replacement, full rewire, plumbing remediation, or structural repair can cost tens of thousands of dollars. In many cases, the market will not reward that expenditure dollar for dollar in the sale price. If you are facing a large capex requirement and the property is not performing strongly, selling before that expenditure becomes unavoidable may produce a better net outcome than investing the capital and continuing to hold.</p>

      <p>You have a better use for the equity. Equity sitting in a low-yielding investment property at 3.5% gross yield is not working hard. If you can access that equity, pay down high-interest debt, fund a business opportunity, or redeploy it into a higher-yielding asset class, the opportunity cost of holding becomes material.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The factors that point toward holding</h2>
      <p>Equally, several conditions suggest that selling would be a mistake.</p>

      <p>The property generates strong rental yield and positive cash flow. A well-located Brisbane inner east investment property that is positively geared, tenanted at above-market rent, and requiring minimal maintenance is a relatively rare asset. The income stream is reliable, the holding costs are manageable, and you are building equity without relying on capital growth to justify the position. Selling a positively geared asset requires a compelling alternative use for the capital.</p>

      <p>You hold a significant unrealised gain that would trigger a large CGT event. If you bought a Hawthorne townhouse 15 years ago and the capital gain is now $800,000, the CGT event on selling is substantial. Depending on your marginal tax rate, the tax liability could be $150,000 to $200,000 or more. The after-tax proceeds need to be genuinely better deployed elsewhere to justify crystallising that tax cost. Holding delays the CGT event, which is a meaningful financial benefit when the gain is large.</p>

      <p>The property is in a corridor with genuine infrastructure-driven growth ahead. If your investment sits within proximity of a major infrastructure project, a new transport corridor, or a rezoning that increases residential density, the outlook for capital growth is materially different from a similar property in a static location. Holding through an infrastructure cycle can significantly outperform selling before the growth is reflected in prices.</p>

      <p>You have no immediate need for the capital. If you are not under cash flow pressure, do not have higher-priority debt to reduce, and have no clear redeployment opportunity for the proceeds, holding is often the correct default. Time in the market generally outperforms timing the market, provided the asset is fundamentally sound.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to model the decision</h2>
      <p>The sell-or-hold analysis comes down to a simple comparison: what do you net after selling, and what return does that produce if redeployed, compared with the return you are currently earning on the investment?</p>

      <p>Start by calculating your net proceeds. Take the estimated sale price, subtract your agent's commission (typically 2-2.5% in Brisbane), your legal and conveyancing costs, and any capital improvements that do not qualify for the CGT discount. Then calculate your CGT liability: the gain (adjusted for capital improvements) multiplied by your marginal tax rate, with the 50% CGT discount applied if you have held for more than 12 months. What remains is the capital you would have available to redeploy.</p>

      <p>Now compare the after-tax net yield you are currently earning on the property (rental income less all holding costs, including mortgage interest, insurance, rates, management fees, and maintenance) against the return you would expect to earn on the redeployed capital. If the redeployment return is materially higher, selling makes financial sense. If it is not, holding is likely the better position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The depreciation schedule consideration</h2>
      <p>Selling an investment property ends your ability to claim depreciation on that asset. If the property has a current depreciation schedule with significant remaining deductions, selling accelerates the end of those deductions. For relatively new properties with large depreciation pools, this is a meaningful cost of selling that is easy to overlook. Ask your accountant to quantify the remaining depreciation deductions and factor the after-tax value of those deductions into your analysis.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The emotional trap</h2>
      <p>Property investors routinely hold poorly performing assets longer than they should because they do not want to crystallise a loss or because they are emotionally attached to the property. Sunk cost is not a financial strategy. The money you have already spent, the original purchase price, the renovations, the years of negative cash flow, is gone regardless of what you do next. The only question that matters is: given where the asset is today, is holding or selling the better decision going forward?</p>

      <p>This is a harder discipline than it sounds. A property that has not grown meaningfully in five years and is costing you money every month can feel like a problem you need to solve by holding on until it comes good. Sometimes that is the right call. But if the fundamentals of the location, the tenant market, or the property type do not support a different conclusion, the disciplined answer may be to sell, take the tax hit, and redeploy the capital more effectively.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Get the right advice before you decide</h2>
      <p>The sell-or-hold decision for an investment property is one of the few property decisions where you genuinely need input from both an accountant and a financial adviser, not just a real estate agent. An accountant can model the CGT event, the depreciation impact, and the after-tax proceeds with precision. A financial adviser can assess whether the alternative uses of the capital are genuinely superior on a risk-adjusted basis. A good real estate agent can give you an accurate estimate of what the property would sell for and what condition it needs to be in to achieve it. You need all three inputs to make a sound decision.</p>

      <p>If you are leaning toward selling, the next step is an accurate market appraisal. Not a rough number, but a properly researched assessment of what comparable properties in your suburb have sold for recently, what condition your property needs to be in to achieve that result, and what the likely campaign strategy looks like. That number anchors the financial model and makes the rest of the analysis concrete.</p>

